World, the Text, and the Indian breaks from this framework by examining Native American literature not for its tribal-national significance but rather its connections to global, transnational, and cosmopolitan forces. Essays by leading scholars in the field assume that Native American literary and cultural production is global in character; even claims to sovereignty and self-determination are made in global contexts and influenced by global forces. Spanning from the nineteenth century to the present day, these analyses of theories, texts, and methods—from trans-indigenous to cosmopolitan, George Copway to Sherman Alexie, and indigenous feminism to book history—interrogate the dialects of global indigeneity and settler colonialism in literary and visual culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aAmerican literaturexIndian authorsxHistory and criticismxTheory, etc. 0aColonization in literature. 0aIdentity (Psychology) in literature. 0aIndian authorsxPolitical and social views. 0aIndians in literature. 0aIndiansxAttitudes. 0aTransnationalism in literature. 4aAmerican Studies : Indigenous Studies. 4aCultural Studies : Cultural Studies. 4aLiterature : Literary Criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Native American.2bisacsh1 aAllen, Chadwick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCheyfitz, Eric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCohen, Matt, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFlint, Kate, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKrupat, Arnold, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLyons, Scott Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLyons, Scott Richard, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 a